other_detail: A friend of mine works for the Ashokan Stream Management Program and heard of your work
request: There's a hemlock forest at the northwest end of the Helderberg Escarpment in Altamont NY that has been dying precipitously. I noticed last winter shredded bark at the base of 10-ish trees, all of which are now standing skeletons. The trees shed their outer bark seemingly over night. I have not noticed Woolly Aldegid and cannot find any evidence of it. I have however, noticed tiny moths this summer that jump from the bark as I approach healthy specimens. I remember seeing the moths last year as well. They appear to be infesting the bark. I also noticed what appear to be woodpecker holes in the bark of the trees immediately after they shed their bark.   I wrote to the DEC Forest Healt team and they responded as follows: Are these moths still out right now? It sounds like they may have been spongy moths as weâ€™ve had a statewide infestation for the past few years and their caterpillars will feed on hemlock needles. If it is spongy moths, what likely happened was the caterpillar feeding on the needles stressed out the trees leading to a hemlock borer infestation. This is common in hemlock dominant forests that are impacted by a stresser like foliage feeding caterpillars, HWA, drought, unfavorable environmental conditions, etc. Hemlock borers take advantage of stressed trees and are able to bypass the their defense mechanisms, starting an infestation. This is soon followed by woodpeckers who begin stripping bark of infested trees to feed on larvae and beetles underneath. This is just another side effect of what invasive species will do to our ecosystem. I also wouldnâ€™t be surprised to know that last yearâ€™s drought has a play in this as well as weâ€™ve seen oaks being heavily effected by it this year, even with all the rain. Unfortunately, thereâ€™s really no way to stop the ball from rolling here other than letting nature take care of itself (predators and parasitoids will eventually control the infestation). I would imagine there will be a couple of trees that will die but the rest will be fine. Iâ€™ve seen this happen in plenty of different scenarios but a couple dead trees is usually the worst of it as forests are very resilient and will ultimately be alright.  I'd like to confirm this diagnosis and discuss the longterm health of the forest.

I'd like to have some trees harvested in a sustainable way. I'd like get a better understanding of how to do so, and an idea of what type of impact(s) that would have on my woodland.

I am looking to increase the health of my woodland and am looking to develop a forest management plan.  I hope to learn more about my woodland and learn best practices for Silviculture tailored to my property.

other_detail: From a volunteer Forester - Dick Gibbs
request: We are concern about the safety of the land due to dead trees and limbs and for its increase fire hazard.
Wildlife habitat improvement

Part of this property was logged immediately before we bought it; part of it is in recovery from logging a few decades ago. We want to get a sense of how healthy the woodland is overall and what we can do to improve its health. There is significant beech bark disease on the property. An opportunity to add native diversity back (such as chestnuts and elms if appropriate for our location) and attract more wildlife would be welcome.
I have an increasing issue with Invasive oriental bittersweet and I am looking for sauggestions on how to control it.
